# === finding-3aee05a3-5635-4aaa-8275-e043363e68cd ===
<urn:tesserai:twin:finding-3aee05a3-5635-4aaa-8275-e043363e68cd> <http://tesserai.io/ontology/createdAt> "2026-03-26T14:48:23.935528Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/topics> "[\"Research industry and international reactions\",\"researcher\"]" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/run_id> "509d6c4d-899c-4d0a-9f3c-4b808bd83541" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/memory_type> "semantic" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/created_at> "2026-03-26T14:48:23.935289+00:00" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/content> "The file write needs your approval. Please approve the write to `/private/tmp/swarm-final-news/research-reactions.md`.\n\nIn the meantime, here is the complete enriched summary from the deep-read:\n\n---\n\n## Enriched Research — Industry & International Reactions\n\n### GPAI Code of Practice: Who's In/Out\n- **Signed (August 2025)**: Microsoft, Google, Amazon, OpenAI, Anthropic + 21 others (26 total)\n- **Refused**: Meta (only major Western holdout) + all Chinese providers\n- Meta consequence: Llama models under **closer AI Office scrutiny**\n- Google signed but expressed concerns about innovation slowdown\n\n### Meta — Most Confrontational Actor (Key Detail Added)\nMeta's lobbying escalation was dramatic: meetings with far-right MEPs went from **1 → 38** in the current parliamentary mandate. They held specific December 2025 meetings with far-right MEPs on the Digital Omnibus. Parallel enforcement: WhatsApp antitrust probe (Jan 2026) + interim measures threatened (Feb 9) → Meta capitulated by allowing rival AIs on WhatsApp, subject to a fee.\n\n### Corporate Europe Observatory: 7-of-8 Match\nThe article maps specific lobbying asks to Omnibus text changes:\n- **Google** lobbied for: ePrivacy Art. 5(3) deletion, GDPR Art. 15-22 \"disproportionate efforts\" loophole, expanded AI Act Art. 10(5) bias detection\n- **Microsoft** lobbied for: narrower pseudonymised data definition, flexible ePrivacy cookie rules\n- **DigitalEurope/CCIA/Dot Europe**: abolish Art. 49 registration, \"legitimate interest\" for AI training, self-assessment exemptions\n\n### US Pressure — Specific Threats\n- Trump: **25% tariffs** on EU tech triggered by €4.3bn Google fine\n- USTR **Jamieson Greer** explicitly named **SAP, Spotify, Mistral** as retaliation targets if EU continued enforcement against US firms\n- VP **J.D. Vance** (Paris AI Summit, Feb 2025): excessive EU AI regulation would \"cripple the industry\"\n- March 20, 2026: Trump administration published comprehensive pro-deregulation AI strategy\n\n### Civil Society: Scale of Opposition\n- **60+ organizations** signed joint letter calling Omnibus \"largest rollback of digital fundamental rights in EU history\"\n- **200+ organizations** signed World Consumer Rights Day statement (March 15) demanding Digital Fairness Act\n- Campaign to remove rapporteur **Aura Salla** (former Meta lobbyist) from Omnibus lead role\n- EDRi framing: omnibus \"plays into the hands of the US administration\"\n\n### International Regulatory Divergence\nThree global camps: EU (risk-based hard law) / US (voluntary/sectoral) / Japan-Singapore (soft governance) / China (state control). Brussels Effect operating — 26 providers meeting EU GPAI Code = de facto global standard. US-EU divergence creates \"fractured Western front\" at critical moment of China competition. USTR threatening European companies (SAP, Spotify, Mistral) with restrictions signals new asymmetric leverage play.\n\n### Compliance Leaders vs. Laggards\n- **Leaders**: Microsoft (invested in compliance infrastructure), Google (cooperative), Finland (full national implementation Dec 2025)\n- **Laggards**: Meta (refusing + under investigation), X/Grok (active enforcement order), 8 of 27 member states (no enforcement contacts 7 months past deadline)\n\nSources:\n- [Corporate Europe Observatory](https://corporateeurope.org/en/2026/01/article-article-how-big-tech-shaped-eus-roll-back-digital-rights)\n- [EU Perspectives — explosive mix](https://euperspectives.eu/2026/02/explosive-mix-us-pressure-and-lobbying-shape-eu-tech-policy/)\n- [EDRi — major rollback](https://edri.org/our-work/commissions-digital-omnibus-is-a-major-rollback-of-eu-digital-protections/)\n- [European Business Magazine — 25% tariff threat](https://europeanbusinessmagazine.com/european-news/eu-prepares-tougher-tech-enforcement-in-2026-as-trump-warns-of-retaliation/)\n- [Modern Diplomacy — Trump AI strategy (Mar 21)](https://moderndiplomacy.eu/2026/03/21/trumps-ai-strategy-exposes-europes-strategic-ambiguity/)\n- [Nemko Digital — Meta rejects GPAI Code](https://digital.nemko.com/news/meta-refuses-gpai-code)" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/confidence> "0.8"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#double> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/agent_id> "4ecfe860-b426-4c7b-8181-bf0dda50483e" ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "The file write needs your approval. Please approve the write to `/private/tmp/swarm-final-news/research-reactions.md`.\n\nIn the meantime, here is the complete enriched summary from the deep-read:\n\n---\n\n## Enriched Research — Industry & International Reactions\n\n### GPAI Code of Practice: Who's In/Out\n- **Signed (August 2025)**: Microsoft, Google, Amazon, OpenAI, Anthropic + 21 others (26 total)\n- **Refused**: Meta (only major Western holdout) + all Chinese providers\n- Meta consequence: Llama models under **closer AI Office scrutiny**\n- Google signed but expressed concerns about innovation slowdown\n\n### Meta — Most Confrontational Actor (Key Detail Added)\nMeta's lobbying escalation was dramatic: meetings with far-right MEPs went from **1 → 38** in the current parliamentary mandate. They held specific December 2025 meetings with far-right MEPs on the Digital Omnibus. Parallel enforcement: WhatsApp antitrust probe (Jan 2026) + interim measures threatened (Feb 9) → Meta capitulated by allowing rival AIs on WhatsApp, subject to a fee.\n\n### Corporate Europe Observatory: 7-of-8 Match\nThe article maps specific lobbying asks to Omnibus text changes:\n- **Google** lobbied for: ePrivacy Art. 5(3) deletion, GDPR Art. 15-22 \"disproportionate efforts\" loophole, expanded AI Act Art. 10(5) bias detection\n- **Microsoft** lobbied for: narrower pseudonymised data definition, flexible ePrivacy cookie rules\n- **DigitalEurope/CCIA/Dot Europe**: abolish Art. 49 registration, \"legitimate interest\" for AI training, self-assessment exemptions\n\n### US Pressure — Specific Threats\n- Trump: **25% tariffs** on EU tech triggered by €4.3bn Google fine\n- USTR **Jamieson Greer** explicitly named **SAP, Spotify, Mistral** as retaliation targets if EU continued enforcement against US firms\n- VP **J.D. Vance** (Paris AI Summit, Feb 2025): excessive EU AI regulation would \"cripple the industry\"\n- March 20, 2026: Trump administration published comprehensive pro-deregulation AI strategy\n\n### Civil Society: Scale of Opposition\n- **60+ organizations** signed joint letter calling Omnibus \"largest rollback of digital fundamental rights in EU history\"\n- **200+ organizations** signed World Consumer Rights Day statement (March 15) demanding Digital Fairness Act\n- Campaign to remove rapporteur **Aura Salla** (former Meta lobbyist) from Omnibus lead role\n- EDRi framing: omnibus \"plays into the hands of the US administration\"\n\n### International Regulatory Divergence\nThree global camps: EU (risk-based hard law) / US (voluntary/sectoral) / Japan-Singapore (soft governance) / China (state control). Brussels Effect operating — 26 providers meeting EU GPAI Code = de facto global standard. US-EU divergence creates \"fractured Western front\" at critical moment of China competition. USTR threatening European companies (SAP, Spotify, Mistral) with restrictions signals new asymmetric leverage play.\n\n### Compliance Leaders vs. Laggards\n- **Leaders**: Microsoft (invested in compliance infrastructure), Google (cooperative), Finland (full national implementation Dec 2025)\n- **Laggards**: Meta (refusing + under investigation), X/Grok (active enforcement order), 8 of 27 member states (no enforcement contacts 7 months past deadline)\n\nSources:\n- [Corporate Europe Observatory](https://corporateeurope.org/en/2026/01/article-article-how-big-tech-shaped-eus-roll-back-digital-rights)\n- [EU Perspectives — explosive mix](https://euperspectives.eu/2026/02/explosive-mix-us-pressure-and-lobbying-shape-eu-tech-policy/)\n- [EDRi — major rollback](https://edri.org/our-work/commissions-digital-omnibus-is-a-major-rollback-of-eu-digital-protections/)\n- [European Business Magazine — 25% tariff threat](https://europeanbusinessmagazine.com/european-news/eu-prepares-tougher-tech-enforcement-in-2026-as-trump-warns-of-retaliation/)\n- [Modern Diplomacy — Trump AI strategy (Mar 21)](https://moderndiplomacy.eu/2026/03/21/trumps-ai-strategy-exposes-europes-strategic-ambiguity/)\n- [Nemko Digital — Meta rejects GPAI Code](https://digital.nemko.com/news/meta-refuses-gpai-code)" ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "The file write needs your approval. Please approve the write to `/private/tmp/swarm-final-news/resea" ;
	a <https://schema.org/SemanticMemory> .


# === finding-63d91826-7a13-48e0-b487-1007a5606446 ===
<urn:tesserai:twin:finding-63d91826-7a13-48e0-b487-1007a5606446> <http://tesserai.io/ontology/createdAt> "2026-03-26T14:41:44.79416Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/topics> "[\"Research EU AI policy debates and new proposals\",\"researcher\"]" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/run_id> "509d6c4d-899c-4d0a-9f3c-4b808bd83541" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/memory_type> "semantic" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/created_at> "2026-03-26T14:41:44.793962+00:00" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/content> "The file write needs your approval. Please approve the write to `/private/tmp/swarm-final-news/research-policy.md`.\n\nHere's a summary of what the deep-read found across the top 8 articles:\n\n---\n\n## Key Enriched Findings\n\n### Digital Omnibus — Institutional Comparison (the main story)\nThe critical new detail is the **institutional divergence** between Parliament, Council, and Commission on specifics:\n\n| Issue | Commission | Council | Parliament |\n|-------|-----------|---------|-----------|\n| Annex III deadline | Conditional (standards-based) | Fixed date | Fixed Dec 2, 2027 |\n| Watermarking grace | Feb 2, 2027 | ~Commission | **Nov 2, 2026** (tightened) |\n| AI literacy | Mandatory | Non-binding | Mandatory (restored) |\n| Nudifier ban | Not proposed | Included | Included |\n| Non-high-risk registration | Eliminate | Reinstate | Reinstate |\n| Bias detection threshold | \"Necessary\" (loosened) | \"Strict necessity\" | \"Strict necessity\" |\n\n**Main trilogue battle**: watermarking timeline (Parliament wants Nov 2026, Council aligned with Commission's Feb 2027).\n\n### Political quotes\n- **Arba Kokalari (EPP, Sweden)**: \"If Europe wants to be competitive, we must increase investment and make it easier to use AI\" — driving simplification with predictability argument\n- **Michael McNamara (Renew, Ireland)**: nudifier ban reflects \"citizens' legitimate expectations\" — framing rights-protection as popular demand\n- **Henna Virkkunen (Commission VP)**: \"Simplification does not mean softening our standards\"\n\n### Copyright Resolution (March 10, 2026)\n- Vote: **460-71** (non-binding)\n- EUIPO to manage machine-readable opt-out register for AI training\n- AI developers must disclose all copyrighted works used in training\n- \"Content entirely generated by AI without human creative input should not qualify for copyright protection\"\n- EU law applies regardless of where training occurred\n- Industry strongly divided — news publishers supportive, AI developers oppose disclosure burden\n\n### Plenary vote today (March 26)\nNo confirmed result yet in available sources — all articles predate the vote. The committee position (101-9-8) was heading to plenary for validation before trilogue.\n\n### AI Liability Directive — formally dead\nAILD withdrawn Feb 2025; Product Liability Directive (transpose by Dec 2026) is now the only mechanism. Pure AI service liability remains a legal gap." ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/confidence> "0.8"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#double> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/agent_id> "512d81ad-37ef-4c1f-a338-edd7d57fc559" ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "The file write needs your approval. Please approve the write to `/private/tmp/swarm-final-news/research-policy.md`.\n\nHere's a summary of what the deep-read found across the top 8 articles:\n\n---\n\n## Key Enriched Findings\n\n### Digital Omnibus — Institutional Comparison (the main story)\nThe critical new detail is the **institutional divergence** between Parliament, Council, and Commission on specifics:\n\n| Issue | Commission | Council | Parliament |\n|-------|-----------|---------|-----------|\n| Annex III deadline | Conditional (standards-based) | Fixed date | Fixed Dec 2, 2027 |\n| Watermarking grace | Feb 2, 2027 | ~Commission | **Nov 2, 2026** (tightened) |\n| AI literacy | Mandatory | Non-binding | Mandatory (restored) |\n| Nudifier ban | Not proposed | Included | Included |\n| Non-high-risk registration | Eliminate | Reinstate | Reinstate |\n| Bias detection threshold | \"Necessary\" (loosened) | \"Strict necessity\" | \"Strict necessity\" |\n\n**Main trilogue battle**: watermarking timeline (Parliament wants Nov 2026, Council aligned with Commission's Feb 2027).\n\n### Political quotes\n- **Arba Kokalari (EPP, Sweden)**: \"If Europe wants to be competitive, we must increase investment and make it easier to use AI\" — driving simplification with predictability argument\n- **Michael McNamara (Renew, Ireland)**: nudifier ban reflects \"citizens' legitimate expectations\" — framing rights-protection as popular demand\n- **Henna Virkkunen (Commission VP)**: \"Simplification does not mean softening our standards\"\n\n### Copyright Resolution (March 10, 2026)\n- Vote: **460-71** (non-binding)\n- EUIPO to manage machine-readable opt-out register for AI training\n- AI developers must disclose all copyrighted works used in training\n- \"Content entirely generated by AI without human creative input should not qualify for copyright protection\"\n- EU law applies regardless of where training occurred\n- Industry strongly divided — news publishers supportive, AI developers oppose disclosure burden\n\n### Plenary vote today (March 26)\nNo confirmed result yet in available sources — all articles predate the vote. The committee position (101-9-8) was heading to plenary for validation before trilogue.\n\n### AI Liability Directive — formally dead\nAILD withdrawn Feb 2025; Product Liability Directive (transpose by Dec 2026) is now the only mechanism. Pure AI service liability remains a legal gap." ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "The file write needs your approval. Please approve the write to `/private/tmp/swarm-final-news/resea" ;
	a <https://schema.org/SemanticMemory> .


# === finding-64a4b142-5459-4b65-beaf-3350ce27c3bd ===
<urn:tesserai:twin:finding-64a4b142-5459-4b65-beaf-3350ce27c3bd> <http://tesserai.io/ontology/createdAt> "2026-03-26T14:44:58.961874Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/topics> "[\"Research industry and international reactions\",\"researcher\"]" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/run_id> "509d6c4d-899c-4d0a-9f3c-4b808bd83541" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/memory_type> "semantic" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/created_at> "2026-03-26T14:44:58.961702+00:00" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/content> "The file write requires your approval. Please approve the write to `/private/tmp/swarm-final-news/research-reactions.md`.\n\nHere's a summary of all findings gathered:\n\n---\n\n## Industry & Stakeholder Reactions — Research Summary\n\n### Big Tech Companies\n\n**Meta** is the most confrontational actor: refused to sign the GPAI Code of Practice (July 2025), citing legal uncertainty and regulatory overreach — the only major AI provider to do so (OpenAI and Anthropic signed). This put Llama models under \"closer scrutiny.\" Meta was then hit with a WhatsApp antitrust investigation (Jan 2026) and threatened with interim measures (Feb 9, 2026) for blocking rival AIs from its API.\n\n**Microsoft** signed the GPAI Code and invested in EU compliance infrastructure. **Google** is under antitrust investigation for AI training data scraping. **X/Grok** received a Commission data retention order (Jan 8, 2026) for Spicy Mode content.\n\n**Siemens CEO Roland Busch** (Mar 24, 2026, FT interview): Called EU AI sovereignty push a potential \"disaster\" — \"You should not throttle innovation speed for sovereignty. This would be a disaster.\" Compared US economy to \"fast-flowing river\" vs. Europe's \"standing water.\"\n\n### Industry Lobbying\nBig Tech spends **€151M/year** on EU lobbying with 890 lobbyists. Corporate Europe Observatory documented that **7 of 8 Omnibus changes mirror Big Tech lobby positions** — weaker data protection, fewer AI checks. DIGITALEUROPE published a joint industry statement broadly welcoming the Omnibus as a competitiveness boost.\n\n### Civil Society\nA united front: **60+ organizations** (EDRi, AlgorithmWatch, ECNL, Liberties.eu, CDT Europe) are calling the Digital Omnibus the \"largest rollback of digital fundamental rights in EU history.\" They signed a joint letter against deleting Article 49(2) (registration exemption) and campaigned to remove rapporteur MEP Aura Salla over her prior role as a **Meta lobbyist**.\n\n### International Reactions\n- **US/Trump**: Most adversarial. Threatened tariffs; US Trade Representative threatened European companies (SAP, Spotify, Mistral) with \"fees or restrictions.\" Called EU actions \"overseas extortion.\" Trump's March 20 AI strategy directly contrasts EU approach.\n- **UK**: \"Compliance-lite\" divergence — no EU-style hard law; Frontier AI Bill planned but softer.\n- **Japan**: Voluntary AI Promotion Act (May 2025); soft governance approach.\n- **China**: Toughened its own rules (Cybersecurity Law, Jan 1, 2026) — sovereign/state-centric path.\n\nSources: DIGITALEUROPE, Corporate Europe Observatory, EDRi, TechCrunch, CNN Business, Irish Times, Brookings, EU ISS, Cryptopolitan, CDT Europe, and others — all URLs included in the file." ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/confidence> "0.8"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#double> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/agent_id> "670ed53a-35eb-42b9-a8f6-0b9d066d1b24" ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "The file write requires your approval. Please approve the write to `/private/tmp/swarm-final-news/research-reactions.md`.\n\nHere's a summary of all findings gathered:\n\n---\n\n## Industry & Stakeholder Reactions — Research Summary\n\n### Big Tech Companies\n\n**Meta** is the most confrontational actor: refused to sign the GPAI Code of Practice (July 2025), citing legal uncertainty and regulatory overreach — the only major AI provider to do so (OpenAI and Anthropic signed). This put Llama models under \"closer scrutiny.\" Meta was then hit with a WhatsApp antitrust investigation (Jan 2026) and threatened with interim measures (Feb 9, 2026) for blocking rival AIs from its API.\n\n**Microsoft** signed the GPAI Code and invested in EU compliance infrastructure. **Google** is under antitrust investigation for AI training data scraping. **X/Grok** received a Commission data retention order (Jan 8, 2026) for Spicy Mode content.\n\n**Siemens CEO Roland Busch** (Mar 24, 2026, FT interview): Called EU AI sovereignty push a potential \"disaster\" — \"You should not throttle innovation speed for sovereignty. This would be a disaster.\" Compared US economy to \"fast-flowing river\" vs. Europe's \"standing water.\"\n\n### Industry Lobbying\nBig Tech spends **€151M/year** on EU lobbying with 890 lobbyists. Corporate Europe Observatory documented that **7 of 8 Omnibus changes mirror Big Tech lobby positions** — weaker data protection, fewer AI checks. DIGITALEUROPE published a joint industry statement broadly welcoming the Omnibus as a competitiveness boost.\n\n### Civil Society\nA united front: **60+ organizations** (EDRi, AlgorithmWatch, ECNL, Liberties.eu, CDT Europe) are calling the Digital Omnibus the \"largest rollback of digital fundamental rights in EU history.\" They signed a joint letter against deleting Article 49(2) (registration exemption) and campaigned to remove rapporteur MEP Aura Salla over her prior role as a **Meta lobbyist**.\n\n### International Reactions\n- **US/Trump**: Most adversarial. Threatened tariffs; US Trade Representative threatened European companies (SAP, Spotify, Mistral) with \"fees or restrictions.\" Called EU actions \"overseas extortion.\" Trump's March 20 AI strategy directly contrasts EU approach.\n- **UK**: \"Compliance-lite\" divergence — no EU-style hard law; Frontier AI Bill planned but softer.\n- **Japan**: Voluntary AI Promotion Act (May 2025); soft governance approach.\n- **China**: Toughened its own rules (Cybersecurity Law, Jan 1, 2026) — sovereign/state-centric path.\n\nSources: DIGITALEUROPE, Corporate Europe Observatory, EDRi, TechCrunch, CNN Business, Irish Times, Brookings, EU ISS, Cryptopolitan, CDT Europe, and others — all URLs included in the file." ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "The file write requires your approval. Please approve the write to `/private/tmp/swarm-final-news/re" ;
