# === memory-18fd4548-b71b-41a8-a3e4-b53d55be82db ===
<urn:tesserai:twin:memory-18fd4548-b71b-41a8-a3e4-b53d55be82db> <http://tesserai.io/ontology/createdAt> "2026-03-26T14:41:44.793408Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/topics> "[\"Research EU AI policy debates and new proposals\",\"Deep-read top policy articles\",\"researcher\"]" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/tool_name> "researcher" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/structured_data> "null" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/run_id> "509d6c4d-899c-4d0a-9f3c-4b808bd83541" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/memory_type> "episodic" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/created_at> "2026-03-26T14:41:44.792760+00:00" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/content> "The file write needs your approval. Please approve the write to `/private/tmp/swarm-final-news/research-policy.md`.\n\nHere's a summary of what the deep-read found across the top 8 articles:\n\n---\n\n## Key Enriched Findings\n\n### Digital Omnibus — Institutional Comparison (the main story)\nThe critical new detail is the **institutional divergence** between Parliament, Council, and Commission on specifics:\n\n| Issue | Commission | Council | Parliament |\n|-------|-----------|---------|-----------|\n| Annex III deadline | Conditional (standards-based) | Fixed date | Fixed Dec 2, 2027 |\n| Watermarking grace | Feb 2, 2027 | ~Commission | **Nov 2, 2026** (tightened) |\n| AI literacy | Mandatory | Non-binding | Mandatory (restored) |\n| Nudifier ban | Not proposed | Included | Included |\n| Non-high-risk registration | Eliminate | Reinstate | Reinstate |\n| Bias detection threshold | \"Necessary\" (loosened) | \"Strict necessity\" | \"Strict necessity\" |\n\n**Main trilogue battle**: watermarking timeline (Parliament wants Nov 2026, Council aligned with Commission's Feb 2027).\n\n### Political quotes\n- **Arba Kokalari (EPP, Sweden)**: \"If Europe wants to be competitive, we must increase investment and make it easier to use AI\" — driving simplification with predictability argument\n- **Michael McNamara (Renew, Ireland)**: nudifier ban reflects \"citizens' legitimate expectations\" — framing rights-protection as popular demand\n- **Henna Virkkunen (Commission VP)**: \"Simplification does not mean softening our standards\"\n\n### Copyright Resolution (March 10, 2026)\n- Vote: **460-71** (non-binding)\n- EUIPO to manage machine-readable opt-out register for AI training\n- AI developers must disclose all copyrighted works used in training\n- \"Content entirely generated by AI without human creative input should not qualify for copyright protection\"\n- EU law applies regardless of where training occurred\n- Industry strongly divided — news publishers supportive, AI developers oppose disclosure burden\n\n### Plenary vote today (March 26)\nNo confirmed result yet in available sources — all articles predate the vote. The committee position (101-9-8) was heading to plenary for validation before trilogue.\n\n### AI Liability Directive — formally dead\nAILD withdrawn Feb 2025; Product Liability Directive (transpose by Dec 2026) is now the only mechanism. Pure AI service liability remains a legal gap." ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/confidence> "1"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#double> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/agent_id> "512d81ad-37ef-4c1f-a338-edd7d57fc559" ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "The file write needs your approval. Please approve the write to `/private/tmp/swarm-final-news/research-policy.md`.\n\nHere's a summary of what the deep-read found across the top 8 articles:\n\n---\n\n## Key Enriched Findings\n\n### Digital Omnibus — Institutional Comparison (the main story)\nThe critical new detail is the **institutional divergence** between Parliament, Council, and Commission on specifics:\n\n| Issue | Commission | Council | Parliament |\n|-------|-----------|---------|-----------|\n| Annex III deadline | Conditional (standards-based) | Fixed date | Fixed Dec 2, 2027 |\n| Watermarking grace | Feb 2, 2027 | ~Commission | **Nov 2, 2026** (tightened) |\n| AI literacy | Mandatory | Non-binding | Mandatory (restored) |\n| Nudifier ban | Not proposed | Included | Included |\n| Non-high-risk registration | Eliminate | Reinstate | Reinstate |\n| Bias detection threshold | \"Necessary\" (loosened) | \"Strict necessity\" | \"Strict necessity\" |\n\n**Main trilogue battle**: watermarking timeline (Parliament wants Nov 2026, Council aligned with Commission's Feb 2027).\n\n### Political quotes\n- **Arba Kokalari (EPP, Sweden)**: \"If Europe wants to be competitive, we must increase investment and make it easier to use AI\" — driving simplification with predictability argument\n- **Michael McNamara (Renew, Ireland)**: nudifier ban reflects \"citizens' legitimate expectations\" — framing rights-protection as popular demand\n- **Henna Virkkunen (Commission VP)**: \"Simplification does not mean softening our standards\"\n\n### Copyright Resolution (March 10, 2026)\n- Vote: **460-71** (non-binding)\n- EUIPO to manage machine-readable opt-out register for AI training\n- AI developers must disclose all copyrighted works used in training\n- \"Content entirely generated by AI without human creative input should not qualify for copyright protection\"\n- EU law applies regardless of where training occurred\n- Industry strongly divided — news publishers supportive, AI developers oppose disclosure burden\n\n### Plenary vote today (March 26)\nNo confirmed result yet in available sources — all articles predate the vote. The committee position (101-9-8) was heading to plenary for validation before trilogue.\n\n### AI Liability Directive — formally dead\nAILD withdrawn Feb 2025; Product Liability Directive (transpose by Dec 2026) is now the only mechanism. Pure AI service liability remains a legal gap." ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "[researcher] The file write needs your approval. Please approve the write to `/private/tmp/sw" ;
