# === memory-2d1a6508-859a-4611-b325-506114b90666 ===
<urn:tesserai:twin:memory-2d1a6508-859a-4611-b325-506114b90666> <http://tesserai.io/ontology/createdAt> "2026-03-26T14:48:23.934608Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/topics> "[\"Research industry and international reactions\",\"Deep-read top reaction articles\",\"researcher\"]" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/tool_name> "researcher" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/structured_data> "null" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/run_id> "509d6c4d-899c-4d0a-9f3c-4b808bd83541" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/memory_type> "episodic" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/created_at> "2026-03-26T14:48:23.933868+00:00" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/content> "The file write needs your approval. Please approve the write to `/private/tmp/swarm-final-news/research-reactions.md`.\n\nIn the meantime, here is the complete enriched summary from the deep-read:\n\n---\n\n## Enriched Research — Industry & International Reactions\n\n### GPAI Code of Practice: Who's In/Out\n- **Signed (August 2025)**: Microsoft, Google, Amazon, OpenAI, Anthropic + 21 others (26 total)\n- **Refused**: Meta (only major Western holdout) + all Chinese providers\n- Meta consequence: Llama models under **closer AI Office scrutiny**\n- Google signed but expressed concerns about innovation slowdown\n\n### Meta — Most Confrontational Actor (Key Detail Added)\nMeta's lobbying escalation was dramatic: meetings with far-right MEPs went from **1 → 38** in the current parliamentary mandate. They held specific December 2025 meetings with far-right MEPs on the Digital Omnibus. Parallel enforcement: WhatsApp antitrust probe (Jan 2026) + interim measures threatened (Feb 9) → Meta capitulated by allowing rival AIs on WhatsApp, subject to a fee.\n\n### Corporate Europe Observatory: 7-of-8 Match\nThe article maps specific lobbying asks to Omnibus text changes:\n- **Google** lobbied for: ePrivacy Art. 5(3) deletion, GDPR Art. 15-22 \"disproportionate efforts\" loophole, expanded AI Act Art. 10(5) bias detection\n- **Microsoft** lobbied for: narrower pseudonymised data definition, flexible ePrivacy cookie rules\n- **DigitalEurope/CCIA/Dot Europe**: abolish Art. 49 registration, \"legitimate interest\" for AI training, self-assessment exemptions\n\n### US Pressure — Specific Threats\n- Trump: **25% tariffs** on EU tech triggered by €4.3bn Google fine\n- USTR **Jamieson Greer** explicitly named **SAP, Spotify, Mistral** as retaliation targets if EU continued enforcement against US firms\n- VP **J.D. Vance** (Paris AI Summit, Feb 2025): excessive EU AI regulation would \"cripple the industry\"\n- March 20, 2026: Trump administration published comprehensive pro-deregulation AI strategy\n\n### Civil Society: Scale of Opposition\n- **60+ organizations** signed joint letter calling Omnibus \"largest rollback of digital fundamental rights in EU history\"\n- **200+ organizations** signed World Consumer Rights Day statement (March 15) demanding Digital Fairness Act\n- Campaign to remove rapporteur **Aura Salla** (former Meta lobbyist) from Omnibus lead role\n- EDRi framing: omnibus \"plays into the hands of the US administration\"\n\n### International Regulatory Divergence\nThree global camps: EU (risk-based hard law) / US (voluntary/sectoral) / Japan-Singapore (soft governance) / China (state control). Brussels Effect operating — 26 providers meeting EU GPAI Code = de facto global standard. US-EU divergence creates \"fractured Western front\" at critical moment of China competition. USTR threatening European companies (SAP, Spotify, Mistral) with restrictions signals new asymmetric leverage play.\n\n### Compliance Leaders vs. Laggards\n- **Leaders**: Microsoft (invested in compliance infrastructure), Google (cooperative), Finland (full national implementation Dec 2025)\n- **Laggards**: Meta (refusing + under investigation), X/Grok (active enforcement order), 8 of 27 member states (no enforcement contacts 7 months past deadline)\n\nSources:\n- [Corporate Europe Observatory](https://corporateeurope.org/en/2026/01/article-article-how-big-tech-shaped-eus-roll-back-digital-rights)\n- [EU Perspectives — explosive mix](https://euperspectives.eu/2026/02/explosive-mix-us-pressure-and-lobbying-shape-eu-tech-policy/)\n- [EDRi — major rollback](https://edri.org/our-work/commissions-digital-omnibus-is-a-major-rollback-of-eu-digital-protections/)\n- [European Business Magazine — 25% tariff threat](https://europeanbusinessmagazine.com/european-news/eu-prepares-tougher-tech-enforcement-in-2026-as-trump-warns-of-retaliation/)\n- [Modern Diplomacy — Trump AI strategy (Mar 21)](https://moderndiplomacy.eu/2026/03/21/trumps-ai-strategy-exposes-europes-strategic-ambiguity/)\n- [Nemko Digital — Meta rejects GPAI Code](https://digital.nemko.com/news/meta-refuses-gpai-code)" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/confidence> "1"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#double> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/agent_id> "4ecfe860-b426-4c7b-8181-bf0dda50483e" ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "The file write needs your approval. Please approve the write to `/private/tmp/swarm-final-news/research-reactions.md`.\n\nIn the meantime, here is the complete enriched summary from the deep-read:\n\n---\n\n## Enriched Research — Industry & International Reactions\n\n### GPAI Code of Practice: Who's In/Out\n- **Signed (August 2025)**: Microsoft, Google, Amazon, OpenAI, Anthropic + 21 others (26 total)\n- **Refused**: Meta (only major Western holdout) + all Chinese providers\n- Meta consequence: Llama models under **closer AI Office scrutiny**\n- Google signed but expressed concerns about innovation slowdown\n\n### Meta — Most Confrontational Actor (Key Detail Added)\nMeta's lobbying escalation was dramatic: meetings with far-right MEPs went from **1 → 38** in the current parliamentary mandate. They held specific December 2025 meetings with far-right MEPs on the Digital Omnibus. Parallel enforcement: WhatsApp antitrust probe (Jan 2026) + interim measures threatened (Feb 9) → Meta capitulated by allowing rival AIs on WhatsApp, subject to a fee.\n\n### Corporate Europe Observatory: 7-of-8 Match\nThe article maps specific lobbying asks to Omnibus text changes:\n- **Google** lobbied for: ePrivacy Art. 5(3) deletion, GDPR Art. 15-22 \"disproportionate efforts\" loophole, expanded AI Act Art. 10(5) bias detection\n- **Microsoft** lobbied for: narrower pseudonymised data definition, flexible ePrivacy cookie rules\n- **DigitalEurope/CCIA/Dot Europe**: abolish Art. 49 registration, \"legitimate interest\" for AI training, self-assessment exemptions\n\n### US Pressure — Specific Threats\n- Trump: **25% tariffs** on EU tech triggered by €4.3bn Google fine\n- USTR **Jamieson Greer** explicitly named **SAP, Spotify, Mistral** as retaliation targets if EU continued enforcement against US firms\n- VP **J.D. Vance** (Paris AI Summit, Feb 2025): excessive EU AI regulation would \"cripple the industry\"\n- March 20, 2026: Trump administration published comprehensive pro-deregulation AI strategy\n\n### Civil Society: Scale of Opposition\n- **60+ organizations** signed joint letter calling Omnibus \"largest rollback of digital fundamental rights in EU history\"\n- **200+ organizations** signed World Consumer Rights Day statement (March 15) demanding Digital Fairness Act\n- Campaign to remove rapporteur **Aura Salla** (former Meta lobbyist) from Omnibus lead role\n- EDRi framing: omnibus \"plays into the hands of the US administration\"\n\n### International Regulatory Divergence\nThree global camps: EU (risk-based hard law) / US (voluntary/sectoral) / Japan-Singapore (soft governance) / China (state control). Brussels Effect operating — 26 providers meeting EU GPAI Code = de facto global standard. US-EU divergence creates \"fractured Western front\" at critical moment of China competition. USTR threatening European companies (SAP, Spotify, Mistral) with restrictions signals new asymmetric leverage play.\n\n### Compliance Leaders vs. Laggards\n- **Leaders**: Microsoft (invested in compliance infrastructure), Google (cooperative), Finland (full national implementation Dec 2025)\n- **Laggards**: Meta (refusing + under investigation), X/Grok (active enforcement order), 8 of 27 member states (no enforcement contacts 7 months past deadline)\n\nSources:\n- [Corporate Europe Observatory](https://corporateeurope.org/en/2026/01/article-article-how-big-tech-shaped-eus-roll-back-digital-rights)\n- [EU Perspectives — explosive mix](https://euperspectives.eu/2026/02/explosive-mix-us-pressure-and-lobbying-shape-eu-tech-policy/)\n- [EDRi — major rollback](https://edri.org/our-work/commissions-digital-omnibus-is-a-major-rollback-of-eu-digital-protections/)\n- [European Business Magazine — 25% tariff threat](https://europeanbusinessmagazine.com/european-news/eu-prepares-tougher-tech-enforcement-in-2026-as-trump-warns-of-retaliation/)\n- [Modern Diplomacy — Trump AI strategy (Mar 21)](https://moderndiplomacy.eu/2026/03/21/trumps-ai-strategy-exposes-europes-strategic-ambiguity/)\n- [Nemko Digital — Meta rejects GPAI Code](https://digital.nemko.com/news/meta-refuses-gpai-code)" ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "[researcher] The file write needs your approval. Please approve the write to `/private/tmp/sw" ;
	a <https://schema.org/EpisodicMemory> .


# === memory-3d9a3655-bcd3-4dec-8604-9685ffd2845b ===
<urn:tesserai:twin:memory-3d9a3655-bcd3-4dec-8604-9685ffd2845b> <http://tesserai.io/ontology/createdAt> "2026-03-26T14:52:37.440121Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/topics> "[\"Review and polish the briefing\",\"Review briefing structure and content\",\"reviewer\"]" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/tool_name> "reviewer" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/structured_data> "null" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/run_id> "509d6c4d-899c-4d0a-9f3c-4b808bd83541" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/memory_type> "episodic" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/created_at> "2026-03-26T14:52:37.439359+00:00" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/content> "I wasn't granted write access. Here is my complete review, which can be used directly:\n\n---\n\n## Briefing Review — `/private/tmp/swarm-final-news/briefing.md`\n\n**Overall**: Well-written, substantive, internally consistent. All statistics and quotes match the prior research findings. No fabricated claims identified. Structure is largely correct. Several sourcing and spec issues require fixes before the briefing is production-ready.\n\n---\n\n### CRITICAL\n\n**1. Six developments instead of the required 3–5**\nThe spec requires 3–5 key developments. The briefing has 6. **Fix**: Merge Developments 5 (Copyright Resolution) and 6 (X/Grok) into a single \"Enforcement Actions and Rights\" section, or demote X/Grok to a bullet under Outlook.\n\n---\n\n### HIGH\n\n**2. Development 5 (Copyright Resolution) has no source line**\nEvery other development ends with `Source:`. Development 5 has none. A verifiable EP resolution (460–71) with a known date has no citation at all. **Fix**: Add `Source: https://www.europarl.europa.eu/` or the specific resolution reference.\n\n**3. Sources 3–6 are root-domain URLs, not article-level**\n- Source 3 (Quinn Emanuel): `/the-firm/publications/` — no article identified\n- Source 4 (Corporate Europe Observatory): `https://corporateeurope.org/` — this article is the *central evidence* for Development 2; a homepage URL is not a citation\n- Source 5 (EDRi joint statement): `https://edri.org/` — specific document exists but is not linked\n- Source 6 (EP resolution): `https://www.europarl.europa.eu/` — resolution number/direct link needed\n**Fix**: Locate specific article URLs, or add title + date so readers can find them.\n\n**4. Sources 7–8 have no URLs at all**\n- Source 7 (March 20 Trump AI strategy): Published by White House/OSTP — a public document with a linkable URL\n- Source 8 (FT/Siemens interview, March 24, 2026): Paywalled, but should cite article title and author\n**Fix**: Add White House URL for the AI strategy; add FT article title/author/date.\n\n---\n\n### MEDIUM\n\n**5. Siemens CEO Busch quote is misplaced in the Meta section**\nDevelopment 3 covers \"Meta's Confrontational Regulatory Posture.\" The final paragraph pivots abruptly to Siemens CEO Roland Busch (March 24, FT) commenting on EU regulation generally — unrelated to Meta. **Fix**: Move to Development 4 (US Trade Pressure) or the Outlook structural trends section where it fits thematically.\n\n**6. Development 4 source is a narrative description, not a URL**\n`\"Source: US USTR statements and Trump administration AI policy documents, February–March 2026\"` is not a citable source. **Fix**: Link to the March 20 national AI strategy document (publicly available).\n\n---\n\n### LOW\n\n**7. Vance February 2025 quote appears in a section labeled February–March 2026**\nThe text does correctly state \"February 2025\" — but opening a 2026-dated section with a year-old quote without transitional framing can confuse readers. **Fix**: Add a bridging sentence like \"The confrontational tone, set at the Paris AI Summit in February 2025, has since acquired concrete form...\"\n\n**8. \"Spicy Mode\" sourced only from secondary research**\nThe X/Grok section attributes the enforcement order to Grok's \"Spicy Mode\" feature. This came from a secondary source summary, not a primary Commission document. **Fix**: Link to the Commission's January 8, 2026 order directly, or add \"according to reports.\"\n\n---\n\n### Verified Accurate (against prior research findings)\n\nAnnex III delay timeline ✓ · IMCO/LIBE vote 101–9–8 ✓ · Council March 13 ✓ · Watermarking Parliament vs. Council divergence ✓ · 7-of-8 lobbying match ✓ · €151M/890 lobbyists ✓ · 26 GPAI signatories ✓ · Meta refusal July 2025 ✓ · WhatsApp interim measures Feb 9, 2026 ✓ · Meta far-right MEP meetings 1→38 ✓ · Greer naming SAP/Spotify/Mistral ✓ · 25% tariff/€4.3bn Google fine ✓ · March 20 AI strategy ✓ · Copyright resolution 460–71 on March 10 ✓ · EUIPO opt-out register ✓ · X/Grok Jan 8, 2026 ✓ · All named quotes (Kokalari, McNamara, Virkkunen, Busch) ✓ · 60+ civil society coalition ✓ · Aura Salla conflict-of-interest ✓ · Art. 112 review Feb 2, 2026 ✓\n\n---\n\n### Summary Table\n\n| Priority | Issue | Required Action |\n|----------|-------|----------------|\n| CRITICAL | 6 developments (spec: 3–5) | Merge or drop one |\n| HIGH | Development 5 missing source | Add EP URL/reference |\n| HIGH | Sources 3–6 are root-domain only | Add specific article URLs |\n| HIGH | Sources 7–8 have no URLs | Add White House URL; cite FT title/author |\n| MEDIUM | Busch quote misplaced in Meta section | Move to Dev 4 or Outlook |\n| MEDIUM | Development 4 no URL-linked source | Link to March 20 AI strategy |\n| LOW | Vance 2025 quote in 2026-dated section | Add transitional framing |\n| LOW | \"Spicy Mode\" from secondary source only | Qualify or link to Commission order |" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/confidence> "1"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#double> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/agent_id> "77302933-ce4f-4279-a2f9-81401204febf" ;
